# define a function for plotting decision boundary
def decision_boundary(clf, ax=None):
    if ax is None:
        ax = plt.gca()
    xlim = ax.get_xlim()
    ylim = ax.get_ylim()
    x_point = np.linspace(xlim[0], xlim[1], 50)
    y_point = np.linspace(ylim[0], ylim[1], 50)
    X, Y = np.meshgrid(x_point, y_point)
    xy = np.vstack([X.ravel(), Y.ravel()]).T
    P = clf.decision_function(xy).reshape(X.shape)
    ax.contour(X, Y, P, colors=['k', 'r', 'k'], levels=[-1, 0, 1], alpha=0.5, linestyles=['--', '-', '--'])
    ax.set_xlim(xlim)
    ax.set_ylim(ylim)
    plt.show()

1.3 Leave-One-Out CV¶

Leave-one-out CV is a special case of k-fold cross-validation, where k = number of samples. The advantage is that we train with almost all the data and test with the remaining one, the result is deterministic. But its disadvantage is that it consumes a lot of computing time, so it is more suitable for situations with a small amount of data.

In [12]:
x = ds_1.drop(['class'],axis=1).to_numpy()
y = ds_1['class'].to_numpy()
In [13]:
# Create list to store the results of each evaluation
scoreList_train = []
scoreList_test = []

loo = LeaveOneOut()
for train_index, test_index in loo.split(x):
    x_train, x_test = x[train_index], x[test_index]
    y_train, y_test = y[train_index], y[test_index]

    # Train the model
    clf_loo = SVC(C=1.0, kernel='linear', gamma='scale', random_state=RANDOM_STATE)
    clf_loo.fit(x_train, y_train)

    # Evaluate the model
    score_train = clf_loo.score(x_train, y_train)
    scoreList_train.append(score_train)

    score_test = clf_loo.score(x_test, y_test)
    scoreList_test.append(score_test)  

print('Mean accuracy on the training set: {:.2f}%'.format(np.mean(scoreList_train)*100))
print('Mean accuracy on the testing set: {:.2f}%'.format(np.mean(scoreList_test)*100))

Mean accuracy on the training set: 72.59%
Mean accuracy on the testing set: 70.00%

1.5 Summary and Explanation¶

C is the complexity parameter, which is also called the penalty parameter in some textbooks.

When C is larger, i.e., the tolerance for outliers in the margin is lower, and the model tends to classify the dataset as correctly as possible, so the generalization ability of the model is worse. When C tends to infinity, we get a hard-margin SVM.

When C is smaller, i.e., the tolerance for outliers in the margin is higher, and the model allows misclassification errors, so the generalization ability of the model is better. We call it soft-margin SVM.

If we compare the above two decision boundary results (C=0.001 and C=60000) with the decision boundary result from chapter 1.2 (C=1.0) we find that:

When C becomes larger, the margin (that is, the two dashed lines in the figure) becomes narrower, because the model at this time cannot allow too many outliers.

Conversely, when C becomes smaller, the margin becomes wider, which contains more outliers from both classes.

When C=0.001, the CV results show that compared with C=1, the model accuracy is reduced, because the model has a high tolerance for misclassification, the margin becomes very wide, a large number of data points are also in the margin, and a large part of this data is discarded as noise.

When C=60000, the CV results show that compared with C=1, the model accuracy does not improve much, although the margin becomes narrow, it does not change too much, and outliers in the margin are also discarded as noise.

In conclusion, we cannot simply say that the smaller the C is better or the larger the better. C does affect the accuracy of the model, but the distribution of data points is also an important factor. In practice, we need to adjust the value of C based on the distribution of the data and what kind of results we want to achieve.

2.1.2.3 Summary and Explanation¶

The principle of 10-fold cross-validation is to randomly divide the data set into 10 parts, of which 9 are used as training set and 1 is used as testing set, and the process is repeated 10 times, so the training data and testing data used are different each time.

The leave-one-out CV is a special kind of k-fold cross-validation, where k = the number of samples.

The advantage of the leave-one-out CV is that its evaluation results are highly deterministic, but it consumes a lot of time.

The traditional 80/20 split method consumes the least time, but the results obtained may be based on coincidence.

10-fold cross-validation finds a balance between the two methods. Although it is not as deterministic as the leave-one-out CV, it saves time, especially when the amount of data is large, it has obvious advantages in speed. Compared with the 80/20 split method, the evaluation results of 10-fold cross-validation are more reliable.

For the 'D2' dataset, since it has a total of 500 data, 10-fold cross-validation is more suitable.

From the above results, it can be observed that the evaluation results of 10-fold CV are close to the evaluation results of leave-one-out CV.

2.3 Summary and Explanation¶

It can be observed from the above experimental results that whether the 'rbf' kernel or the 'poly' kernel is selected, the performance of their models is much better than that of the linear kernel model, and the performance of the 'rbf' kernel is even better. It can also be observed from the generated decision boundary figure that the decision boundary (i.e. the red line in the figure) of the 'rbf' kernel model classifies the data more perfectly than the 'poly' kernel model.

The 'rbf' kernel is also called a Gaussian kernel in some textbooks. Its principle is to map data that are non-splittable in a low-dimensional space to a high-dimensional space and then find a hyperplane to classify the data. In this experiment, the points of the 'D2' dataset are distributed in a ring shape, so in the 2D plane, it is difficult for us to find a 'line' to classify, when the 'rbf' kernel function is used, the points in the 2D plane are mapping to 3D space, in higher dimensions we can easily find a hyperplane to split the data. Therefore, in daily applications, when we are not sure whether the data is linearly distributed, the 'rbf' kernel becomes the first choice.

# Create list to store the results of each evaluation
scoreList_train = []
scoreList_test = []

loo = LeaveOneOut()
for train_index, test_index in loo.split(x):
    x_train, x_test = x[train_index], x[test_index]
    y_train, y_test = y[train_index], y[test_index]

    # Train the model

    # Evaluate the model

    scoreList_train.append(score_train)

    score_test = clf_loo.score(x_test, y_test)
    scoreList_test.append(score_test)

3.3 Summary and Explanation¶

From the above experimental results, it can be observed that the performance of the 'rbf' kernel model after parameter tuning is slightly lower than that of the linear kernel model after parameter tuning. At the same time, the accuracies of both models are lower than the linear kernel model with default parameters, but the difference is not significant.

Since the distribution of data points also affects the final result, in the 'D3' dataset, we observed that the point distribution is already clear, and the amount of data that crosses between the two classes is very small, so whether the linear kernel or the 'rbf' kernel is used, even with the default parameters, higher accuracy can already be obtained.

In theory, the 'rbf' kernel can approximately simulate a linear kernel. In general, if the data is linearly distributed, we choose the linear kernel model; when the data distribution is ambiguous, the 'rbf' kernel model is usually the preferred solution due to its wide applicability and high performance.

For the description and detailed analysis of parameter C, please refer to chapter 1.5.

For the 'rbf' kernel model, gamma is also an important parameter that defines how much influence a single training example has. When the gamma is too large, the model is easy to overfit and the generalization ability is poor. Conversely, when the gamma is too small, the model can be made more complicated by increasing the C value.

Since the nature of machine learning is a trade-off between training accuracy and generalization ability, for the 'rbf' kernel model, the C value and the gamma value jointly affect the performance of the model.
